AB  - The NSW North Coast is the traditional country of the Bundjalung people. The Byron Bay embayment has had a long history of coastal development since European colonisation. Belongil spit was subdivided into 200 lots with 33 feet (approximately 10 m) frontages in 1886. The first jetty was constructed off Jonson Street in 1888 and was removed in 1949. A second jetty was built (between Don and Manfred Streets) in 1928, was severely damaged in 1954 and was removed in 1972. The war memorial pool near Jonson Street was opened in 1966, with the pool, adjacent car park and surf life saving club protected by a seawall. Byron Shire Council has had a policy of "Planned Retreat" in some planning documents dating back to 1988, whereby development that is at risk from coastal erosion/recession is required to be removed at the owners' expense. Numerous legal cases have resulted from disputes between beachfront residents and Council. All private development on Belongil spit now has some form of rock, concrete or geotextile container coastal protection-with most of these structures not designed to contemporary engineering standards. A partial seawall also fronts the Marine Parade foreshore at Wategos Beach. Four substantial coastal management studies have been undertaken for Byron Bay since the mid-1970s, with a recent study indicating that Belongil is receding at approximately 0.45 m/year. Sophisticated economic modelling indicates that almost $190 million of private assets are vulnerable to coastal erosion/recession to 2050. There are numerous technically and economically viable management options for existing developed areas over typical planning periods. This paper documents the coastal processes which prevail at Byron Bay, the history of studies undertaken and potential management options, including their economic feasibility. The paper examines the impediments to the implementation of effective coastal management over the past 40 years. Â© Australasian Coasts and Ports 2017 Conference. All rights reserved.
