AB  - Barrier islands are naturally dynamic features that change in shape length,width, height. and geographic position, and orientation in response to waves, relative sea-level rise, sediment, supply and, to it lesser degree, winds and currents, Although basic causes of barrier island retreat and area have been identified in the literature, there has been limited success at quantifying how these processes couple to generate the observed barrier island behavior. This paper examines general coastal engineering concepts and models and discusses their ability (capabilities and limitations) to quantify sediment losses and forecast the performance of barrier island nourishments in the mixed sediment barriers of the state of Louisiana. The use of littoral budgets is discussed its it tool to understand past losses and to predict performance of proposed modifications to the coast, A conceptual dynamic morphosedimentary model (DMSM) that describes dominant processes and sediment losses during barrier island retreat is proposed. The methodology proposed by the DMSM suggests significantly lower volumetric losses than what had been previously assumed for the Louisiana coast by other authors supporting significant cost savings in beach nourishment projects.
