AB  - The thirty states that border the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, the Gulf of Mexico, and the Great Lakes house 85 percent of the nation's population. The movement of people to coastal regions is accelerating with especially large growth in 'sunbelt' coastal states such as California and Florida. As the development of coastal regions has intensified, coastal erosion has become increasingly important. This article discusses the causes of erosion, outlines solutions and future solutions. The Coastal Engineering Research Center (CERC) is expanding a wave gaging network to obtain the data needed for planning and designing shore protection and other coastal projects. CERC is also conducting research on nonstructural methods to protect shores. CERC is studying the processes that affect beachfills, hoping to improve their longevity and reduce their cost. CERC is also researching methods to evaluate the effects of structures on adjacent shorelines. Recently developed mathematical models can be used to look at shoreline evolution over decades with and without a wide variety of structures in place. Major experiments with participation by federal and state agencies and several universities have been conducted at CERC's Field Research Facility. These and future experiments and research at CERC, universities, and other agencies promise to significantly improve our understanding of coastal processes and enhance our ability to protect U.S. shores from coastal floods, storm damage, and erosion.
