AB  - Indian Ocean Region is geo-strategically placed at the helm of global power politics owing to its vital Sea Lines of Communications. For both littoral and foreign nations, who seeks to use this region to maintain their strategic game, Indian Ocean acts as strategic backwaters. However, in the process of geopolitical rivalry, certain crucial maritime security concerns, beyond the traditional military threats, are overlooked. Based on reports of climate change, this study examines certain concerns, which are collectively termed as Non-Traditional maritime security threats. These threats, such as rise in sea levels, ocean acidification and unregulated fishing are not merely environmental threats, but are security threats as well. These threats are compounding at a high rate and negligence of the same possibly will result in a catastrophe that may not only affect the political economy of Indian Ocean littoral nations, but also of the global economy. This is essentially because Indian Ocean caters as the trade arteries of global trade, as more than 80\% of global energy trade passing over the region. This study further argues that the littoral nations of the region are pre-occupied in a geopolitical struggle for power, which limits the scope of any efficient region-wide, climate-security cooperation. Finally, this study concludes that at the regional strategic policy consultations, maritime security should be inclusive of these Non-Traditional maritime concerns also, which could act as an impetus for betterment of inter-regional relations.
