AB  - A major challenge for ecosystem-based climate change adaptation and sustainable resource management in the Pacific is reaching the thousands of coastal communities. If we continue to work island by island, community by community, with intensively facilitated management processes, we will run out of time to achieve the necessary changes for a sustainable future. An element of the solution to addressing climate change impacts is encompassed in the communities themselves through the sharing of intergenerational stories both within and among communities. Recording and documenting community membersâ€™ stories and local perspectives through the production of participatory videos creates a tangible, visual product that facilitates self-awareness and further exchange. This paper looks at the uptake of this idea of a group of small island communities in Milne Bay, PNG. This concept is currently being facilitated in Milne Bay, PNG under the USAID-funded Pacific-American Climate Fund. Essential project equipment, which included waterproof digital cameras, a laptop and a solar panel, were distributed to a community school on three island communities. Conservation International (CI) staff are supporting communities in video taking and production of peopleâ€™s stories, a process that is leading towards community empowerment behind the lens. The uptake of becoming â€˜videographersâ€™ did not occur spontaneously however and considerable facilitation has been required. Initial findings indicate that, although community members were previously aware of environmental changes, the experience of recording and presenting their own views on video reinforced the prevalence and importance of these changes. Â© 2017, Springer International Publishing AG.
