AB  - The existing revetment wall at St Bees on the UK Cumbrian coast was breached in three places during high waves and tides. Interim repairs involved filling the breaches with large rocks while earlier reconstruction plans were re-assessed. A vital railway link runs along the top of the revetment wall. Repair and reconstruction works had to be undertaken without disrupting rail services. The old 12m high caly core revetment wall was strengthened by grouting the voids and it was used as the core of a new structure. The new structure features wave dissipating rock armour facing on the lower half, and precast concrete units on the upper half to prevent overtopping. Design and construction of the new wall structure are described in detail.
