TY  - Conference
TI  - Darwin city waterfront breakwater - innovative cost effective design to allow overtopping
JO  - 9th National Conference On Hydraulics In Water Engineering 2008
PY  - 2008
VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - The tidal range in Darwin's harbour is up to eight metres. This can create an environment where there are large distances between land-based structures and low water level, giving a disconnection between the people and the water. The Darwin City Waterfront vision was to create a standing body of water that would be at the highest possible level to create close and enjoyable relationships between water, buildings and people. This is achieved by creating a static water body, the lagoon. This static body of water also delivers the Architect's reflectivity requirements for the new world-class Darwin Convention and Entertainment Centre, further enhancing its iconic nature. The breakwater creates the lagoon and therefore doubles as an earth dam and that needed to be high enough that it would not be damaged during major storms, but still low enough that people at the Convention Centre and the public domain areas could see over the wall out to sea. To overcome these competing demands, the 635 m long breakwater was designed as an overtopping structure with its crest at the lowest possible level. To protect the leeward side from the tremendous forces expected by overtopping waves, an innovative capping design was used to reduce the transmission of energy of the overtopping waves. The net result is a considerable reduction in the wave energy prior to it reaching the rock armour on the leeward face of the breakwater. Aside from achieving the desired aesthetic effect of the lowered breakwater, this allowed the rock protection on the leeward face to be reduced from 2.5 tonne to 0.5 tonne affording a considerable saving to the project. Â© 2008 Hydraulics.
DO  - NA
SN  - NA
KW  - cost effectiveness;  hydraulics;  tides;  water levels;  wave energy conversion, capping design;  cost effective design;  land based structures;  overtopping waves;  public domains;  static water;  tidal ranges;  world class, breakwaters
